To sort a column in a `wxGrid` when clicking on its header, you can handle the event `wxEVT_GRID_LABEL_LEFT_CLICK`. Here's an example of how you can implement this functionality:

1. Connect the event to a handler function in your grid class constructor:

```cpp
// Constructor of your grid class
MyGridClass::MyGridClass(wxWindow* parent, wxWindowID id, const wxPoint& pos, const wxSize& size)
    : wxGrid(parent, id, pos, size)
{
    // Connect the event to the handler function
    Bind(wxEVT_GRID_LABEL_LEFT_CLICK, &MyGridClass::OnLabelLeftClick, this);
}
```

2. Implement the event handler function:

```cpp
void MyGridClass::OnLabelLeftClick(wxGridEvent& event)
{
    int col = event.GetCol();

    if (col == m_lastSortedCol) {
        // The column was already sorted, just reverse the order
        m_sortOrder = !m_sortOrder;
    } else {
        // Sort the column in ascending order by default
        m_sortOrder = true;
    }

    m_lastSortedCol = col;

    // Sort the grid based on the clicked column
    SortByColumn(col);

    // Refresh the grid to reflect the changes
    Refresh();
}
```

3. Implement the `SortByColumn` function to perform the sorting based on the clicked column:

```cpp
void MyGridClass::SortByColumn(int col)
{
    // Implement your sorting logic here

    // Example logic: Sort rows in ascending order based on the clicked column
    if (m_sortOrder) {
        SortByAscending(col);
    } else {
        SortByDescending(col);
    }
}
```

4. Implement the sorting methods `SortByAscending` and `SortByDescending` based on your specific sorting requirements.

By following these steps, you'll be able to sort the columns in your `wxGrid` by clicking on their headers. Remember to adapt the sorting methods (`SortByAscending` and `SortByDescending`) according to your own sorting logic.

